04424nam a22005535i 9780822387060DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223870607 a10.1515/97808223870602doi  a(DE-B1597)554023  a(OCoLC)1229160756  a(OCoLC)1226679037  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN2287.W46bC55 2006 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a792.702/8/0921 aChude-Sokei, Louis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Last "Darky" :bBert Williams, Black-on-Black Minstrelsy, and the African Diaspora /cLouis Chude-Sokei. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Black Minstrel, Black Modernism -- t2. Migrations of a Mask -- t3. Theorizing Black-on-Black Cross-Culturality -- t4. The Global Economy of Minstrelsy -- t5. In Dahomey -- t6. Claude McKay's Calypso -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Last "Darky" establishes Bert Williams, the comedian of the late nineteenth century and early twentieth, as central to the development of a global black modernism centered in Harlem's Renaissance. Before integrating Broadway in 1910 via a controversial stint with the Ziegfeld Follies, Williams was already an international icon. Yet his name has faded into near obscurity, his extraordinary accomplishments forgotten largely because he performed in blackface. Louis Chude-Sokei contends that Williams's blackface was not a display of internalized racism nor a submission to the expectations of the moment. It was an appropriation and exploration of the contradictory and potentially liberating power of racial stereotypes.Chude-Sokei makes the crucial argument that Williams's minstrelsy negotiated the place of black immigrants in the cultural hotbed of New York City and was replicated throughout the African diaspora, from the Caribbean to Africa itself. Williams was born in the Bahamas. When performing the "darky," he was actually masquerading as an African American. This black-on-black minstrelsy thus challenged emergent racial constructions equating "black" with African American and marginalizing the many diasporic blacks in New York. It also dramatized the practice of passing for African American common among non-American blacks in an African American-dominated Harlem. Exploring the thought of figures such as Booker T. Washington, W. E. B. Du Bois, Marcus Garvey, and Claude McKay, Chude-Sokei situates black-on-black minstrelsy at the center of burgeoning modernist discourses of assimilation, separatism, race militancy, carnival, and internationalism. While these discourses were engaged with the question of representing the "Negro" in the context of white racism, through black-on-black minstrelsy they were also deployed against the growing international influence of African American culture and politics in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aBlackface entertainerszUnited States. 0aMinstrel showszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387060.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles